events.description: Following the Battle of Bakhamra between Alids and Abbasids near Kufa, the Alid rebellion ends with the death of Ibrahim, brother of Isa ibn Musa.

events.description: The Swiss Anabaptist Movement is founded when Conrad Grebel, Felix Manz, George Blaurock, and about a dozen others baptize each other in the home of Manz's mother in Zürich, breaking a thousand-year tradition of church-state union.
events.html: • 1525 – The Swiss Anabaptist Movement is founded when Conrad Grebel, Felix Manz, George Blaurock, and about a dozen others baptize each other in the home of Manz's mother in Zürich, breaking a thousand-year tradition of church-state union.[2]

events.description: Following the Affair of the Placards, the French king leads an anti-Protestant procession through Paris.

events.description: Sweden and Prussia sign the Treaty of Stockholm.
events.html: • 1720 – Sweden and Prussia sign the Treaty of Stockholm.[5]

events.description: The Teatro Filarmonico in Verona is destroyed by fire, as a result of a torch being left behind in the box of a nobleman after a performance. It is rebuilt in 1754.
events.html: • 1749 – The Teatro Filarmonico in Verona is destroyed by fire, as a result of a torch being left behind in the box of a nobleman after a performance. It is rebuilt in 1754.[6]

events.description: Abdul Hamid I becomes Sultan of the Ottoman Empire and Caliph of Islam.
events.html: • 1774 – Abdul Hamid I becomes Sultan of the Ottoman Empire and Caliph of Islam.

events.description: The first American novel, The Power of Sympathy or the Triumph of Nature Founded in Truth by William Hill Brown, is printed in Boston.
events.html: • 1789 – The first American novel, The Power of Sympathy or the Triumph of Nature Founded in Truth by William Hill Brown, is printed in Boston.

events.description: After being found guilty of treason by the French National Convention, Louis XVI of France is executed by guillotine.
events.html: • 1793 – After being found guilty of treason by the French National Convention, Louis XVI of France is executed by guillotine.

events.description: The RMS Tayleur sinks off Lambay Island on her maiden voyage from Liverpool to Australia with great loss of life.
events.html: • 1854 – The RMS Tayleur sinks off Lambay Island on her maiden voyage from Liverpool to Australia with great loss of life.[7]

events.description: The Tati Concessions Land, formerly part of Matabeleland, is formally annexed to the Bechuanaland Protectorate, now Botswana.
events.html: • 1893 – The Tati Concessions Land, formerly part of Matabeleland, is formally annexed to the Bechuanaland Protectorate, now Botswana.

events.description: New York City passes the Sullivan Ordinance, making it illegal for women to smoke in public, only to have the measure vetoed by the mayor.
events.html: • 1908 – New York City passes the Sullivan Ordinance, making it illegal for women to smoke in public, only to have the measure vetoed by the mayor.

events.description: The first Monte Carlo Rally takes place.
events.html: • 1911 – The first Monte Carlo Rally takes place.

events.description: Kiwanis International is founded in Detroit.
events.html: • 1915 – Kiwanis International is founded in Detroit.

events.description: A revolutionary Irish parliament is founded and declares the independence of the Irish Republic. One of the first engagements of the Irish War of Independence takes place.
events.html: • 1919 – A revolutionary Irish parliament is founded and declares the independence of the Irish Republic. One of the first engagements of the Irish War of Independence takes place.

events.description: Albania declares itself a republic.
events.html: • 1925 – Albania declares itself a republic.

events.description: Sir Isaac Isaacs is sworn in as the first Australian-born Governor-General of Australia.
events.html: • 1931 – Sir Isaac Isaacs is sworn in as the first Australian-born Governor-General of Australia.

events.description: Finland and the Soviet Union sign a non-aggression treaty.
events.html: • 1932 – Finland and the Soviet Union sign a non-aggression treaty.[8]

events.description: Sparked by the murder of a German officer in Bucharest, Romania the day before, members of the Iron Guard engaged in a rebellion and pogrom killing 125 Jews.
events.html: • 1941 – Sparked by the murder of a German officer in Bucharest, Romania the day before, members of the Iron Guard engaged in a rebellion and pogrom killing 125 Jews.

events.description: The Jewish resistance organization, Fareynikte Partizaner Organizatsye, based in the Vilna Ghetto was established.
events.html: • 1942 – The Jewish resistance organization, Fareynikte Partizaner Organizatsye, based in the Vilna Ghetto was established.[9]

events.description: As part of Operation Animals, British SOE saboteurs destroy the railway bridge over the Asopos River, and guerrillas of the Greek People's Liberation Army ambush and destroy a German convoy at the Battle of Sarantaporos.
events.html: • 1943 – As part of Operation Animals, British SOE saboteurs destroy the railway bridge over the Asopos River, and guerrillas of the Greek People's Liberation Army ambush and destroy a German convoy at the Battle of Sarantaporos.[10]

events.description: The Flag of Quebec is adopted and flown for the first time over the National Assembly of Quebec. The day is marked annually as Québec Flag Day.
events.html: • 1948 – The Flag of Quebec is adopted and flown for the first time over the National Assembly of Quebec. The day is marked annually as Québec Flag Day.

events.description: American lawyer and government official Alger Hiss is convicted of perjury.
events.html: • 1950 – American lawyer and government official Alger Hiss is convicted of perjury.

events.description: The catastrophic eruption of Mount Lamington in Papua New Guinea claims 2,942 lives.
events.html: • 1951 – The catastrophic eruption of Mount Lamington in Papua New Guinea claims 2,942 lives.[11]

events.description: The first nuclear-powered submarine, the USS Nautilus, is launched in Groton, Connecticut by Mamie Eisenhower, the First Lady of the United States.
events.html: • 1954 – The first nuclear-powered submarine, the USS Nautilus, is launched in Groton, Connecticut by Mamie Eisenhower, the First Lady of the United States.

events.description: Avianca Flight 671 crashes at Montego Bay, Jamaica airport, killing 37 people.
events.html: • 1960 – Avianca Flight 671 crashes at Montego Bay, Jamaica airport, killing 37 people.

events.description: A coal mine collapses at Holly Country, South Africa, killing 435 miners.

events.description: A B-52 bomber crashes near Thule Air Base, contaminating the area after its nuclear payload ruptures. One of the four bombs remains unaccounted for after the cleanup operation is complete.
events.html: • 1968 – A B-52 bomber crashes near Thule Air Base, contaminating the area after its nuclear payload ruptures. One of the four bombs remains unaccounted for after the cleanup operation is complete.

events.description: The current Emley Moor transmitting station, the tallest free-standing structure in the United Kingdom, begins transmitting UHF broadcasts.
events.html: • 1971 – The current Emley Moor transmitting station, the tallest free-standing structure in the United Kingdom, begins transmitting UHF broadcasts.

events.description: Commercial service of Concorde begins with the London-Bahrain and Paris-Rio routes.
events.html: • 1976 – Commercial service of Concorde begins with the London-Bahrain and Paris-Rio routes.

events.description: Iran Air Flight 291 crashes in the Alborz Mountains while on approach to Mehrabad International Airport in Tehran, Iran, killing 128 people.
events.html: • 1980 – Iran Air Flight 291 crashes in the Alborz Mountains while on approach to Mehrabad International Airport in Tehran, Iran, killing 128 people.[13]

events.description: Production of the DeLorean sports car begins in Dunmurry, Northern Ireland, United Kingdom.
events.html: • 1981 – Production of the DeLorean sports car begins in Dunmurry, Northern Ireland, United Kingdom.

events.description: Galaxy Airlines Flight 203 crashes near Reno–Tahoe International Airport in Reno, Nevada, killing 70 people.
events.html: • 1985 – Galaxy Airlines Flight 203 crashes near Reno–Tahoe International Airport in Reno, Nevada, killing 70 people.[14]

events.description: The U.S. House of Representatives votes 395–28 to reprimand Newt Gingrich for ethics violations, making him the first Speaker of the House to be so disciplined.
events.html: • 1997 – The U.S. House of Representatives votes 395–28 to reprimand Newt Gingrich for ethics violations, making him the first Speaker of the House to be so disciplined.

events.description: War on Drugs: In one of the largest drug busts in American history, the United States Coast Guard intercepts a ship with over 4,300 kilograms (9,500 lb) of cocaine on board.
events.html: • 1999 – War on Drugs: In one of the largest drug busts in American history, the United States Coast Guard intercepts a ship with over 4,300 kilograms (9,500 lb) of cocaine on board.

events.description: Ecuador: After the Ecuadorian Congress is seized by indigenous organizations, Col. Lucio Gutiérrez, Carlos Solorzano and Antonio Vargas depose President Jamil Mahuad. Gutierrez is later replaced by Gen. Carlos Mendoza, who resigns and allows Vice-President Gustavo Noboa to succeed Mahuad.

events.html: • 2003 – A 7.6 magnitude earthquake strikes the Mexican state of Colima, killing 29 and leaving approximately 10,000 people homeless.[15]

events.description: NASA's MER-A (the Mars Rover Spirit) ceases communication with mission control. The problem lies in the management of its flash memory and is fixed remotely from Earth on February 6.

events.html: • 2005 – In Belmopan, Belize, the unrest over the government's new taxes erupts into riots.
